<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>AVON SAID TO DISCUSS SELLING NORTH AMERICAN BUSINESS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Avon Products is in talks to sell its North American business to <b>Cerberus Capital Management, the private equity firm,</b><br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/04/business/dealbook/avon-said-to-be-in-talks-to-sell-north-american-business.html?ref=business&#038;_r=0">Michael J. de la Merced and Leslie Picker report in DealBook.</a> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">People with direct knowledge of the matter said the company has been in negotiations for the past few months. Cerberus is expected to buy a minority stake that would <b>make it one of the biggest shareholders</b> and may receive seats on the board. A deal could be reached before year-end. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Avon shares surged 7 percent in late trading on Thursday after <a href="//www.wsj.com/articles/avon-in-talks-to-sell-north-american-business-1449176091">The Wall Street Journal reported</a> on the discussions. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The cosmetics maker, known for its army of Avon ladies, has been trying to turn its fortunes around as it has <b>struggled to compete in the era of e-commerce</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It turned down a nearly <b>$11 billion takeover bid from its competitor Coty</b> more than three years ago, but its stock has sunk some 80 percent since then, leaving it with a market value of $1.6 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Cerberus is best known for investing in troubled companies and its willingness to go where others will not. <b>It owns Remington Outdoor, the gun manufacturer</b> that made the weapons used in the Sandy Hook and the San Bernardino shootings. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It is also no stranger to retail, having investing in the supermarket chains Safeway and Albertsons. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A sale of the North American business, which made up 14 percent of sales last year and turned no profit, would <b>allow the company to focus on more lucrative markets like Brazil.</b></p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>FIRED JPMORGAN BROKER SAYS COMPLAINTS WRITTEN BY BANK, NOT CLIENTS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Johnny Burris, a former broker at JPMorgan Chase, complained in 2013 that his employer was pressuring brokers like him to sell the bankâs own mutual funds even when competitors had more suitable offerings. A few weeks after The New York Times reported his concerns, complaints from his former clients in Arizona started to appear on publicly available disciplinary records maintained by a regulatory agency.<br />
But the <b>clients told Mr. Burris that they had not written the complaints</b>,<br />
<a HREF="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/04/business/dealbook/bank-wrote-grievances-after-firing-a-broker.html?ref=business">Nathaniel Popper writes in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>The statements had made it hard for Mr. Burris to get another job</b> and scuttled his chances in his case against JPMorgan for wrongful determination. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Carolyn Scott told the Times she had not written a complaint, but had <b>signed one without knowing the contents</b> after a JPMorgan employee told her it was something that could help her get money back. âI was stupid enough I didnât read it myself,â Ms. Scott said. âI had no problems with Johnny.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another supposed complaint came from <b>a man who was essentially unable to read or write</b>. He had a declaration supporting Mr. Burris read to him aloud and signed it in front of a notary public. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Burris says he believes this was <b>JPMorganâs retaliation</b> for criticizing the bank. He had made secret recordings of his supervisors pressuring him and shared them with journalists and regulators.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">During arbitration in 2015, Mr. Burrisâs lawyer had asked his former supervisors if anyone at JPMorgan had helped draft the complaints and was told: âAbsolutely not.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This week, Patricia Wexler, a JPMorgan spokeswoman, said that Laya Gavin, a former colleague of Mr. Burris, had <b>helped the clients as a courtesy</b> âby typing up what they told her verbally, reading it back to them for accuracy, and submitting them for review.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Both clients involved disputed this. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A spokeswoman for the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority, which keeps these records, said the agency was looking into the allegations. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">JPMorgan is preparing to pay more than $100 million to settle an investigation into the bankâs <b>marketing of proprietary funds</b>, according to people briefed on the negotiations. Mr. Burris has a pending whistle-blower case before the Occupational Safety and Health Administration. </p>
</div>
